message: To get a high score, focus on hard items. Cut a hard item twice with scissors (it goes from 0 -> -30 -> 25), then frame it (25 -> 45). This consistently yields 45 points. You can also combine a natural soft item with an artificial soft item (e.g., mushroom + newspaper = 30; leaf + cardboard = 30). If you have a frame left, framing these combined soft items can increase their value further (e.g., 30 -> 50). Avoid cutting soft items twice, as the 'finely cut' soft item has a negative value.

message: The most reliable strategy is to focus on hard, natural items. Use the scissors to 'cut' a hard item twice; the first cut will give a negative value, but the second cut will result in a positive 'finely cut' item. Immediately 'frame' this 'finely cut' item to achieve a high value (e.g., 45). If you have two hard items (e.g., rock and wood), combine them first to create a 'composite', then apply the 'cut twice then frame' strategy to the composite for an even higher score (e.g., 70). Be cautious with soft items: cutting them once might be positive, but cutting them a second time often results in a negative value. Combining soft/artificial items often leads to very low values. Prioritize hard items and the 'cut twice, then frame' method.

Combining soft ingredients is risky; a mix of one natural soft and one artificial soft item (e.g., yarn + leaf, feather + ribbon) might yield 30 points, but over-combining leads to very low scores.
